Class JsFlashPlayer

All Implemented Interfaces:
ObjectLike
public class JsFlashPlayer
extends DOM.FlashPlayer.Prototype

An opaque class representing JavaScript client-side objects of the global JsClient.FlashPlayer class.

An object of this class represents a Flash movie embedded in a web page and the instance of the Flash plug-in that is playing that movie. You can obtain an object of this class using JsDocument.getElementById(String) to get the <embed> or <object> tag that embeds the movie in the web page.

Once you have obtained an object of this class, you can use the various methods it defines to control playback of the movie and to interact with it by setting and querying variables. Note that JsFlashPlayer methods all begin with a capital letter, which is not a common naming convention in Java and JavaScript.

Author:
J.J.Liu (Jianjun Liu) at http://www.jscripter.org

public final void GotoFrame(java.lang.Number frameNumber)

Jumps to the specified frame number in the movie.

This method skips to the specified frame of the movie, or skips to the last available frame, if the specified frame has not been loaded yet. To avoid this indeterminate behavior, use PercentLoaded() to determine how much of the movie is available.

Parameters:

Pan

public final void Pan(java.lang.Number dx,
                      java.lang.Number dy,
                      java.lang.Number mode)

Moves the viewport of the movie.

The Flash player defines a viewport through which Flash movies are visible. Typically, the size of the viewport and the size of the movie are the same, but this may not be not the case when SetZoomRect(Number, Number, Number, Number) or Zoom(Number) have been called: those methods can alter the viewport so that only a portion of the movie shows through.

When the viewport is showing only a portion of the movie, this method moves (or "pans") the viewport so that a different portion of the movie shows. This method doesn't allow you to pan beyond the edges of a movie, however.

Parameters:
dx - The horizontal amounts to pan.
dy - The vertical amounts to pan.
mode - Specifies how to interpret the dx and dy values. If this argument is 0, the other arguments are taken as pixels. If this argument is 1, the others are percentages.
Since:
1.0
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must convert the instance invocation of this method directly into a JavaScript invocation on its current object instance without changing the method name, but expanding variable arguments, if any, into comma-separated values.

SetZoomRect

public final void SetZoomRect(java.lang.Number left,
                              java.lang.Number top,
                              java.lang.Number right,
                              java.lang.Number bottom)

Sets the area of the movie displayed by the Flash player.

This method defines the movie's viewport, that is, it specifies a sub-rectangle of the movie to appear in the Flash player. Flash movies are measured in a unit known as the twip. There are 20 twips to a point and 1,440 twips to an inch.

Parameters:
left - The X-coordinate, in twips, of the upper-left corner of the viewport.
top - The Y-coordinate, in twips, of the upper-left corner of the viewport.
right - The X-coordinate, in twips, of the lower-right corner of the viewport.
bottom - The Y-coordinate, in twips, of the lower-right corner of the viewport.
Since:
1.0
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must convert the instance invocation of this method directly into a JavaScript invocation on its current object instance without changing the method name, but expanding variable arguments, if any, into comma-separated values.

Zoom

public final void Zoom(java.lang.Number percentage)

Changes the size of the movie's viewport.

This method scales the viewport by a specified percentage. Arguments between 1 and 99 reduce the size of the viewport, which makes objects in the movie appear larger. Arguments greater than 100 enlarge the viewport (but never beyond the size of the movie) and make objects in the movie appear smaller. As a special case, the argument 0 restores the viewport to full size, so that the entire movie is visible.

Parameters:
percentage - The percentage by which to scale the viewport, or 0 to restore the viewport to its full size.
Since:
1.0
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must convert the instance invocation of this method directly into a JavaScript invocation on its current object instance without changing the method name, but expanding variable arguments, if any, into comma-separated values.
